    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Alveolar Fricatives in Coda",
          "textSize": "heading-one"
        }
      ],
      "align": "center"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "horizontal-separator",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Overview: /s/ Reduction ",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "One of the most widely discussed features of Caribbean Spanish and a central resource in reggaetón is the variable realization of syllable-final /s/ (e.g., "
        },
        {
          "text": "lo",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "italic": true,
          "text": "s",
          "bold": true,
          "underline": true
        },
        {
          "italic": true,
          "text": " mi"
        },
        {
          "italic": true,
          "text": "s",
          "bold": true,
          "underline": true
        },
        {
          "italic": true,
          "text": "mo"
        },
        {
          "italic": true,
          "text": "s",
          "bold": true,
          "underline": true
        },
        {
          "text": ").  Historically, this feature traces back to Southern Spain in Seville and Andalusia more broadly, where processes of consonant weakening began as early as the 16th century in lower-class speech before spreading upward through the social hierarchy and outward through colonial expansion. As a result, varieties of Spanish across the Caribbean inherited this feature as part of a broader phonological profile shaped by Andalusian input."
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Phonetically, /s/ reduction is often described as a weakening pathway "
        },
        {
          "text": "[s] → [h] → [∅]. ",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "text": "That is, a fully articulated sibilant [s] may be realized as such (e.g., [los 'mismos]), an aspirated [h] ([loh 'mihmoh]), and, in some cases, deleted altogether ([lo 'mimo]). In Puerto Rico, /s/ reduction falls within Stage 3 of Lipski's weakening pathway, meaning it canonically occurs in most cases of pre-consonantal coda and some pre-vocalic codas, but it does not occur in the onset position. In addition to these three  allophones, /s/ can also be realized as a voiced fricative [z] and aspiration [ɦ], as well as a glottal stop [ʔ]  ([loʔ ˈmihmoʔ]). that is unique to Puerto Rico. Importantly, the lack of /s/ does not create confusion between words that without /s/ are homophonous (e.g., "
        },
        {
          "text": "mismo",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " and "
        },
        {
          "text": "mimo",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": "), as speakers utilize several phonetic strategies to distinguish forms, including vocalic and consonantal lengthening and consonantal strengthening (e.g., "
        },
        {
          "text": "mismo",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " ['mim:o] vs "
        },
        {
          "text": "mimo",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " ['mimo]). "
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
