    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "S-Reduction can be measured acoustically using a combined Center of Gravity (COG) and Standard Deviation (SD) Measurement in Hertz (Hz). The COG measurement tells us the average frequency of the sound, whereas the SD tells us the expansion or range of that average. That is, a sound with a very high COG and a low SD is a very high frequency flow of air moving through a relatively small airway. The prototypical alveolar variant has a high COG, typically ranging between 6-10kHz. As /s/ reduces toward /h/ and eventually /ø/, the COG drops drastically. Below are spectrograms that showcase a full /s/, as well as two forms of deletion: one where the \"place\" of /s/ in the word is trace-marked with a pause, and another where the segment is elided entirely. "
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
