    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "/s/ in Puerto Rico ",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The alternation between these forms is not random. Rather, their distribution is conditioned by phonological environment, as well as social and stylistic factors. In Puerto Rico, /s/ variation is deeply embedded in social evaluation. Traditionally, full [s] is associated with formality, education, and institutional authority, while aspiration [h] and deletion [∅] are linked to informality and everyday speech. However, these associations are not stable or uniform. Aspirated [h], for example, is often positively evaluated as an authentic marker of Puerto Rican identity, particularly in casual contexts. Deletion [∅], by contrast, is more heavily stigmatized, frequently associated with lack of education or lower socioeconomic status. At the same time, these values are highly context-dependent and mediated by who is perceived to be using the feature."
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "url": "https://drive.google.com/file/d/1AzZxTlX98SzLxXRQPwKlhQANKeLMB2hP/view?usp=sharing",
      "caption": "An Indexical Field of /s/ reduction in Puerto Rico",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ],
      "align": "center"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Taken together, /s/ reduction illustrates how a phonological process that originated as a regional feature becomes reinterpreted through social practice. In everyday speech and especially in musical performance, these variants are not simply inherited—they are strategically deployed. This is why /s/ reduction plays such a central role in reggaetón: it has become enregistered as part of the genre’s sonic identity, a stylistic resource that signals Caribbeanness, urbanity, and authenticity, regardless of where the performer is from.\n"
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "horizontal-separator",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "center",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-two",
          "text": "/s/ in Reggaetón "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Coda s-reduction is a very common phonological feature of reggaetón's production. It's salience is so visible that in online lyric transcriptions, you will commonly find people mark words with etymological /s/ with an ' to indicate a reduction (e.g., \""
        },
        {
          "text": "no me mire' así",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": "\"). Because of its salience, and the fact that this feature is by far the most well-researched case of phonological variation in the Spanish-speaking world, it is perhaps unsurprising that most of the research on reggaetón singing styles has recruited /s/ as the unit of analysis. The following examples will showcase the findings of these studies. "
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The findings on /s/ reduction can be summarized as such: This feature is an enregistered resource for constructing and performing artistic authenticity and alignment with the broader reggaetón soundscape. This claim draws from research from two major experimental designs: "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "numbered-list",
      "children": [
        {
          "type": "list-item",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "Research comparing reggaetón's vocal style to that of other Hispano-Caribbean genres. "
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "list-item",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "Research comparing performances by Puerto Rican/Caribbean artists and reggaetón artists from non-s-reducing dialects of Spanish."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-three",
          "text": "Sibilants' Mark on the Genre"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The first line of research to examine the semiotic function of /s/ reduction across the genre categories used by global music industries to organize and market various forms of Caribbean popular music. In particular, Powell (2025) compared the allophonic distribution of this feature in the performances of three mainstream artists from different parts of the insular Caribbean: Ivy Queen (Puerto Rico), Natti Natasha (Dominican Republic), and Srta. Dayana (Cuba). Each of these artists was selected because they frequently perform not just reggaetón, but in genres that are marketed explicitly as \"Latin Pop\" or \"Tropical\" (an umbrella category designed to account for folkloric musics like salsa, plena, merengue, bachata, rumba, and the like). For each artist, the rate of /s/ reduction significantly increased in songs marketed as reggaetón/urbano music, while drastically decreasing in songs marketed as \"tropical\" (see below): "
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "/s/ is seen as a genre-specific index of artistic affiliation. This means that scholars have found artists reduce /s/ significantly more when performing reggaetón but not other genres. Below are examples of Puerto Rican artists specifically who showcase this pattern. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Ivy Queen "
        }
      ]
